Practical 8a - Geostatistical Modelling for Childhood malaria in the Gambia

Bayesian modelling for spatial and spatio-temporal data

This practical uses the data from (Diggle et al. 2018) concerning a study in the Gambia that was designed to assess the effectiveness of the National Impregnated Bednet Programme in reducing child morbidity and mortality from malaria.

Data were collected on 2035 children living in 65 different villages in the Gambia. Blood samples were taken for each child and measured for the presence of malarial parasites. Covariate data included the child’s age, whether or not they regularly slept under a bed net, and if so, whether this was treated (with permethrin insecticide). Two village-level covariates were also measured: an indicator of whether the village belonged to the Primary Health Care system, and a measure of the greenness of the village environment.

These data are freely available from the geoR package (Ribeiro Jr. and Diggle 2001) in R (R Core Team 2022). For this practical, the data are collected in a .RData file called gambia_data.RData.

The gambia_data.RData file includes a set of objects: + M = 2035 children + N = 65 villages

  • gambia is a data.frame that includes the following 7 variables:

x = x-coordinate of the village (UTM)

y = y-coordinate of the village (UTM)

pos= presence (1) or absence (0) of malaria in a blood sample taken from the child

age = age of the child, in days

bednetis the bed net use and is in 3 categories: 1 = doesn’t sleep under bed net 2 = sleeps under untreated bed net 3 = sleeps under bed net impregnated with permethrin insecticide

green = satellite-derived measure of the greenness of vegetation in the immediate vicinity of the village

phc = binary indicator: 1/0 = village does/doesn’t belong to Primary Health Care system

  • gambia_data.RData includes also an indicator variable (between 1 and 65) called village indicating which village the children belong to.

In this practical we will assess if sleeping under bed nets reduce risk of malaria. Also we are interested in evaluating if other child- or village-level covariates help explain risk of malaria and if there is evidence of spatial structure in the between-village variation which would indicate partly an environmental explanation.

  • To start with, create a separate subdirectory to save your files created during this tutorial (e.g. setwd(“~/Labs/Lab_3a”)).

To do this we first create an simple features, sf, object from the prev, specifying the original UTM coordinate reference system, "+proj=utm +zone=28", and use st_transform to reproject this data to “+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84”`

5. Geostatistical Modelling in R-INLA using the SPDE approach

We now fit a spatial model to the Gambia malaria prevalence and we estimate that at unsampled locations, quantifying the effect of altitude. The number of positive results obtained at locations (i.e. villages), is conditional on the true prevalence of malaria and follows a Binomial distribution. Let \(Y_i\) be the observed prevalence of malaria in village \(i\), and \(N_i\) be the total number of people tested in each village \(i\), for \(i=1, \dots, 65\) (we simplify here the notation, as presented in slide 5 of Session3.1). We assume the following model:

\[\begin{equation} \begin{aligned} Y_{i} & \sim \hbox{Binomial}(p_{i}, N_{i}); \;\;\; i=1,...,65\\ \hbox{logit} (p_{i}) & = \beta_{0} + \beta_1 X_{i} + \xi_i\\ \boldsymbol{\xi} &\sim GF(\boldsymbol{0}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}) \\ \end{aligned} \end{equation}\]

where \(p_{i}\) is the true malaria prevalence to be estimated and predicted, \(\beta_{0}\) denotes the intercept and \(\beta_1\) is the regression coefficient associated to altitude. The spatial random effect \(\mathbf{\xi}\) is a stationary zero-mean Gaussian process with Matérn covariance function.

  1. To implement this model, we need to construct a triangulated mesh to cover The Gambia. To build the mesh, we use the inla.mesh.2d() function from INLA, with:

  • loc: matrix of point locations to be used as initial triangulation vertices,

  • max.edge: the largest allowed triangle edge length,

  • cutoff: the minimum allowed distance between points.

  • We can plot the mesh using the plot function.

  1. Build SPDE model
  • We build the SPDE model on the mesh using the inla.spde2.matern function.

Where alpha is related to the smoothness parameter through \(\alpha = \nu + d/2\) and setting constr = TRUE imposes an “integrate-to-zero” constraint.

  1. Generate the index set
  • To generate the index set we use the inla.spde.make.index function with spatial effect spatial and number of vertices equal to as in the SPDE model.
  1. Build the projection matrix
  • To build the projection matrix A we use the function inla.spde.make.A.
  1. Specifying the prediction locations
  • To create a set of prediction coordinates across The Gambia, we can aggregate our elev dataset into larger pixel sizes and get the coordinates using the crds function
ra = terra::aggregate(elev, fact = 5, fun = mean)
plot(ra)

pred.points = crds(ra)
dim(pred.points)
## [1] 411   2
  • Then, as in part 3, we extract the altitude at these prediction points, using terra::extract and create a matrix of the prediction points
elev.points = terra::extract(elev, pred.points)
head(elev.points)
elev.points = cbind(pred.points, elev.points)

head(pred.points)
pred.coords = as.matrix(elev.points[,c("x", "y")])
  1. Again using the inla.spde.make.A function to create the prediction projection matix A.pred
A.pred = inla.spde.make.A(mesh = mesh, loc = pred.coords)
  1. Create INLA stacks

Using the inla.stack function, we create a stack for estimation from the prev data and the prediction stack from elev.points. Thenput the stacks together using inla.stack again

  1. Specify the model formula

We specify the INLA model formula with a covariate intercept tem, 0 + b, adding altitude as a covariate, altitude, and the SPDE model term, f(s.index, model = spde)

  1. Run the INLA model

We run the INLA model using the inla function, formulating as the proposed model, where the model family in Binomial (family = "binomial"), with numtrials number of trials (Ntrials = numtrials), and logit link function (control.family = list(link = "logit")). We read in the stack data, predictors, and matrix A as usual.

6. Mapping the Predicted Malaria Prevalence.

  1. Extract the indexes of the predicted points from the INLA stack, using the inla.stack.index function.
pred.index = inla.stack.index(stack = full.stack, tag = "pred")$data

  1. Extract the posterior predicted mean and 95% credible intervals from results$summary.fitted values.

  2. Join the posterior means and credible interval values to the prediction point coordinates and create an sf object

  3. Again we can map the malaria prevalence either using using ggplot2 and tmap or the mapview package

  • First we create a SpatRaster from the predicted data pred.sf
library(stars) ## package used to create and manipulate rasters

pred.rast <- st_rasterize(pred.sf %>% dplyr::select(pred.mean, CI.low, CI.high, geometry)) #function to rasterize an sf object

pred.rast$pred.mean[pred.rast$pred.mean == 0] <- NA #replace zeros with NAs
plot(pred.rast)

  • Then we plot, using geom_stars for ggplot and tm_raster for tmap
ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(data = GMB,  col = "black") +
  geom_stars(data = pred.rast) + 
  scale_fill_distiller(palette = "RdYlGn", na.value = NA)

tmap_mode("view")
tm_shape(GMB) + tm_borders(lty="solid", col="black") +
  tm_shape(pred.rast) + tm_raster(col = "pred.mean", palette="RdYlGn") + tm_layout(legend.outside = TRUE)
  • Alternatively, in mapview:
mapview(pred.rast, zcol = "pred.mean")
